.TH _PRINTF 3 "2026" "Holberton Printf" "Holberton School Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
as described below.
.sp
The function writes the output to
.BR stdout ,
the standard output stream.
.sp
The function returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte).
On error, a negative value is returned.
.SH FORMAT
The format string is a character string composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not
.BR % ),
which are copied unchanged to the output stream; and conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments.
.PP
Each conversion specification is introduced by the character
.BR % ,
and ends with a conversion specifier.
.SS Conversion Specifiers
.TP
.B c
The
.I int
argument is converted to an
.I unsigned char
and the resulting character is written.
.TP
.B s
The
.I "char *"
argument is expected to be a pointer to a string. Characters from the string are written up to (but not including) a terminating null byte.
.TP
.B %
A
.B '%'
is written. No argument is converted.
.TP
.B d, i
The
.I int
argument is converted to signed decimal notation.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR printf (3)
.SH AUTHOR
Dhay Aldhwayan , Shatha Alanzi 
